   "source": [
    "**MANAGE findings:**\n",
    "\n",
    "-Both mitigation strategies had to suffer some accuracy compared to the baseline (although very slight), but reduced the disparate impact.\n",
    "\n",
    "-Reweighing sacrifices less accuracy but has a lower disparate impact than the threshold optimizer, which acheives about perfect parity. \n",
    "\n",
    "-Neither mitigation reaches perfect fairness across all metrics, which supports the idea that it is very difficult for multiple fairness critera to be satisfied at the same time when base rates differ among groups (as they did for male vs. female). \n",
    "\n",
    "The decision of *which mitigation to deploy* is a judgment call. An internal team optimizing for accuracy will lean toward Reweighing. An external auditor focused on legal exposure and reducing disparity under the four-fifths rule will lean toward Threshold Optimization. **The mitigation choice is itself a governance decision**, and that brings us to the central question of this audit.\n"
   ]
